The study examines the fertility history of American couples in metropolitan America and the motivational connections between the environment and fertility decisions and behavior.

Phase I looks at the social and psychological factors thought to relate to differences in fertility. Phase II focuses on why some couples stopped at two children while others had a third or fourth child during the first and second phase. Phase III examines how well attitudes and events of the early marriage determined the record of the later years of child bearing.
